    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "I hear you, and I want to validate that feeling of futility without the usual \"loneliness\" label, because sometimes the pain is sharper when it's not just about missing people but about the sheer weight of your own existence in a place that feels foreign and indifferent. It's a very specific kind of ache, like trying to speak to a wall that is made of your own thoughts.\n\nYou are absolutely right that in a city where you don't speak the language, you can feel like a glitch in the system, a temporary error code that the city's massive, humming machinery doesn't even register. The feeling of being a \"ghost\" isn't about being alone; it's about being *unseen* by the very reality you're trying to navigate.\n\nBut I do want to gently suggest that even if the city doesn't notice you, the universe of your own experience is vast and real, even if it feels small right now. Sometimes, the most profound moments of clarity happen when we stop trying to fit into the machine and just sit with the feeling of being a ghost in it.\n\nIf you ever feel like you need to talk to someone who understands this specific kind of existential dread, there are always people willing to",
      "source": "target",
